Focal Flowers

Focal flowers are the main or featured blooms in a floral arrangement. They are typically larger, more prominent flowers that draw the eye and serve as the focal point of the design. Examples include roses or hydrangeas Focal flowers often dictate the color scheme and overall theme of the arrangement.

Filler Flowers

Filler flowers are smaller blooms that are used to fill in gaps and add texture to floral arrangements. They complement the focal flowers and help create a balanced and full look. Filler flowers can be used to add volume and depth to the arrangement, and are available in a variety of shapes and colors.

Line Flowers

Line flowers are long, slender blooms that add height and structure to floral arrangements. They create visual interest and can be used to establish the overall shape and form of the design. Line flowers are typically placed vertically or diagonally in the arrangement to create movement and flow.

Greenery

Greenery refers to foliage, branches, and other botanical elements that are used to enhance and complement floral arrangements. Greenery adds texture, color, and volume to the design and helps create a natural and organic look. It can include leaves, ferns, eucalyptus, ivy, and other types of foliage. Greenery is often used as a backdrop to highlight the beauty of the focal and filler flowers.
